<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-132-882  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 132 882.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Educational Technology  March 1989 v29 n3 p18(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Preparing teachers to use technologies: can universities meet thechallenge?andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gooler, Dennis.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Universities can meet the challenge of preparing teachers to usetechnology, but not without considerable effort and commitment.andO;Currently, a great disparity exists among the hundreds of USuniversity programs focusing on teacher training.andP;  The issuesinvolved include: deciding what technology and technologyapplications student teachers should learn, whether they shouldlearn about technology as content or as instructional tools, wherein the curriculum should technology training be placed, who shouldteach technology and how should technology be taught.andP;  Theproblems include lack of resources, academic politics, anduniversity faculties who themselves do not understand or usetechnology.andP;  Universities must decide what is to be taught abouttechnology, provide the necessary resources, train their facultyand commit to an instructional design and development process thatresults in courses or other learning packages.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Teacher EducationComputer EducationColleges and UniversitiesTechnologyEducation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>